thought to have killed at least 7 intrepid explorers, including some of Thurgadin’s finest dwarven heroes.  The explosion causing the avalanche had been a mighty one, seemingly as though the giants and the dragons had at long last reached a climax in their thousand year war, come together, and exploded as one great machine.  But Melba knew that was not what had happened.<br>
<br>
Melba had been exploring some of the remoter caves with her husband, Damdor.  It had been days since they’d seen anyone else, aside from the small camp of three dwarves who were tracking some sort of rabid bear.   They’d headed into the caves two days ago, and hadn’t returned as yet.   They’d also seen a group of Rangers go in, but that had been a week ago.  They’d said they were going “spelunking”.  (“More like ‘getting lost and dying’” Damdor grumbled.)<br>
<br>
The Lyteheart’s were running low on food.  Melba wanted to stay out, exploring the caves a bit more.   She didn’t mind so much, eating the terrible things she foraged.  They’d eaten worse.  At least here the dead things were quickfrozen, and didn’t rot, like in Kunark.<br>
<br>
Damdor mumbled something about a hot meal and some hot cider.    Melba sighed and stirred the embers of the fire.  <br>
<br>
“You go on back to town, hon.  I’ll be fine here.”<br>
<br>
Damdor watched his wife across the flickering fire.  “Alone??  I should go alone??  No.  No, you must come with me.”  She gave him a look.  He fidgeted.  “Are you sure you don’t want to come back with me?  A night in a warm bed, with room service, would do us both no end of good!” he grinned.<br>
<br>
She smiled fondly back at him.  “Aye, that’s what you’re wanting, isn’t it?  A nice warm, soft bed, and some huevos rancheros for brekkies….”<br>
<br>
He smiled and sipped his tea.  They’d used the last of the tealeaves, for this meal.  “And we need more tea.”<br>
<br>
Melba picked up the small canister they used to store their tea, and shook it.  Just crumbs.  She nodded.  “You go on, darling.  I’ll be fine!  I always am.   I’m going to track just a little way in, and then I’ll come back to camp and stay here.  Please don’t worry!  You’ll be back in two days, anyhow, won’t you.  It’s only a half days ride into town, I’m sure.  We’ve been going in circles, and we’re much closer than you think….”<br>
<br>
He nodded “True, darling, true.   And if I can’t have you to guide me, at least I have my trusty compass….”  He raised his eyebrows, grinned, and shook his rusty old compass at her.  He was funning her again.  She threw a tiny snowball at him, which bounced off the top of his knee.  Her stomach rumbled.<br>
<br>
“I heard that.    I’ll leave most of the fishrolls here with you, ok?  Ok, then.  I’m off.  I’ll be back before you know it!”  Damdor struggled to his feet, squelching in the muddy slush which made up the floor of their camp.  They’d found a small, secluded cavern, just off the entrance to the larger one they meant to explore.  Surely an old home for small bears, at one time.  No indication of anything living in there, recently, though.  Which worried Damdor, but didn’t seem to bother Melba.  The roof was slanted just right so that they could have a nice fire in the mornings and at night…and they had their bedrolls to keep them dry.  Home away from home.<br>
<br>
Damdor stepped around the fire, and held his hand out to his wife, who took it and rose from her cross-legged position on her folded-over bedroll.  She threw her arms around him and kissed him soundly.  “Bring me some of those little frosty dwarf cakes, will you?  The ones with the cream filling?”  She smiled and tweaked his chin.  He nodded, and looked down at her fingers, which were nimbly (for all it was so cold) fastening his armguards at his wrist.  “Don’t take your plate, darling, It’ll slow you down, and you’ll only freeze.”  He nodded again, looking at her fondly.  <br>
<br>
“Taking my helmet, though, ok mom?” he chided, putting it on.  She gave it two affectionate raps with her knuckle.   It rang hollowly.<br>
<br>
“Ok, buckethead,” she smiled.  “At least take some of these breadrolls, and the rest of this tea.<br>
<br>
“I’ll be fine…” he muttered.  “Rabbit jerky” he indicated his pack.   She wrinkled her nose.<br>
<br>
“Off you go, then!  Tunare guide you!” she called after him, as he picked his way down the ledge of the main cave, and off into the snow.  <br>
<br>
“Tunare my eye….” He grumbled to himself.  He stopped, however, and turned to look at her.  The day was just dawning, and for once it was clear, with no threat of snow.  The sun made Melba’s ivy green armor glow a warm purple.   She smiled and waved from the cave entrance, pushing her hair back out of her eyes in the slight breeze coming from the cave.  For some reason, Damdor turned fully to face her, and executed a jaunty warrior’s salute.  She laughed and blew him a kiss.  Then, she saluted back, ranger style.<br>
<br>
He trudged off into the snow, whistling a happy tune about killing Dark Elves at night in Kithicor.<br>
<br>
Grinning, Melba turned and went back into the little cave.  The fire had died almost completely.  There was plenty of kindling in the area, but she thought it would be a superb idea to find some actual timber to burn.  She and Damdor both thought that these caves had once been mined….perhaps there were mining shores down there, fallen from the walls or ceiling, that would burn nicely.   That was her plan for the day:  real firewood.<br>
<br>
She packed away the uneaten half of her breakfast muffin, and grabbed a small bag of dried fruit and a water flask.  She picked up her Wurmslayer…thought better of it and set it against the cavern wall.  Instead, she strapped her Short Ykesha to her beltloop.  She also grabbed up her staff.  She buffed herself up a bit with strength, agility, and good old Spirit of the Wolf, just in case she had to run from rabid bears or crazed spelunkers.  “Ranger, Ranger, run away!  Live to fight another day!” she sang, giggling at the old ditty she’d heard sung once, in a tavern frequented by Warriors.<br>
<br>
She kicked her bedroll into the corner with Damdor’s, away from the dwindling fire.  She strapped her pack onto her back, and ducked under the small cave’s entrance, heading left and down into the entrance of the main cavern.  The persistent dripping of water off the stalactites reminded Melba that Spring was nigh, and soon, given some sunlight and encouragement, maybe even this bleak land would turn green and bloom.  At least, she hoped so.  They’d seen so much snow, lately….<br>
<br>
Melba marked her pathway down the cavern with a piece of coal.  She made the sign of Tunare every time she took a turn down into another tunnel.  So far, no tracks indicating mining cars…but that didn’t mean anything.  “This may not even be the principal entrance” she thought.<br>
<br>
She was about a mile into the cavern, traveling quickly, finding nothing, when she felt a slight rocking.  Dust puffed down from the tunnel’s ceiling, and a few pebbles skittered down the sloping path, rolling into darkness.  <br>
<br>
That was odd, she thought.   There’s been no indication of volcanic activity in this area.  Maybe an earthquake?<br>
<br>
She continued on.<br>
<br>
And on.<br>
<br>
An hour later, having found nothing, Melba decided to head back.  Tomorrow, she would go down the other branching tunnel.  These caverns couldn’t be completely empty.  Could they?<br>
<br>
Fifteen minutes into her ascent, she saw a glowing light ahead of her.  Company!  She thought, brightly.  And yet, ever cautious, she unsheathed her Ykesha, stepped back into the shadows and hid herself until she could be sure.  Strangely, nothing showed on her tracking.  She crept along the side of the cave, towards the increasing glow.  It was blueish, with a green tint.  She could make out a form, now.  Was it a person?  A person on fire??  <br>
<br>
“Show yourself!”  she called.  And, as an afterthought, cried “I am armed!”<br>
<br>
The light pulsed once and dimmed.  “No need for that, child.” A voice said, with a slight laugh.  “Put it away, or you’ll hurt yourself in the dark, silly ranger!”<br>
<br>
Irked, Melba stepped a bit closer to the dimming light.  That voice.  She knew that voice.  She’d heard it once, in her dreams, long ago.<br>
<br>
Melba took another tentative step towards the light.  And another.  The glowing thing advanced on her a bit, until the form solidified.  She dropped her sword with a dull thud onto the cavern floor.<br>
<br>
“Tunare??”<br>
<br>
“Aye, child, it’s me.  There’s no time to talk.  Get your sword, and go.  Run.  Back up the way you came.  Follow the marks you made, clever girl. But get out of here, now!”<br>
<br>
“But….”<br>
<br>
The glowing lady held out her hand.  “No buts.  Go.  Now.  If you value your life, go!  I can do nothing to stop what’s to happen, but at least I can warn you.”  She faded a bit more.  “It’s a direct order, child.  Take heed.”    Tunare disappeared.<br>
<br>
Melba, eyes still huge and brimming with tears at the wonder of Tunare, leaned down quickly, grabbed her Ykesha, and ran.   Miles to go, still, it seemed.  There was another jolt, and it caused her to stagger and grab uselessly for the cavern wall.  Her Spirit of the Wolf spell wore off.  “Damn” she swore quietly, and hurriedly re-cast.   “Damn!” she said as it took, and she took off running again, just as another jolt, larger this time, shook the cavern.  Finally, finally she could see the glare of the clean white snow of the cavern entrance.  With another burst of speed, she was up the ramp and almost to the cave mouth when a bigger jolt than any of the others hit.  Before her eyes, a wall of snow appeared and the cavern mouth closed, for all of Norrath as if she was being swallowed up by a giant monster made of ice and stone.<br>
<br>
****<br>
<br>
Two days later, Damdor returned to the spot where he had left his wife.  The cave was gone, somehow.  He knew, though, that he was in the right place.  Sticking out at an angle, 6 feet up the wall of snow, was Melba’s Wurmslayer.   He swore furiously and began to dig.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
