 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umelbatoast.showPublicProfile?language=EN>melbatoast</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 103<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/3/01 4:18:14 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Trapped</span><hr size=1> “Well, crap,” Melba said quietly, sitting on the floor of the cave, shaking the dust out of her hair.  <br>
<br>
She’d been knocked flat backwards by the force of the cave-in, and her head had hit the floor hard enough to knock her out…but for how long??  How long had she been unconscious?  All her buffs were gone, so it had been at least 20 minutes.  The air in the dark cavern was still and black; not a glimmer of light anywhere. Just the ever-present dripping, and the settling of rocks.<br>
<br>
Melba wondered why Tunare hadn’t warned her sooner about the avalanche/explosion/ whatever it was.  Why the glowing and the fussing and the laughing?  Surely she’d known Melba would never make it out of the cavern in time!  Or were the gods fallible, too?  Something to ponder…but at another time, surely.<br>
<br>
Melba tentatively got to her feet, and, breathing hard through her nose to get the dust and snow out, she checked to make sure nothing was broken.  Her head had a huge bump, but other than that, nothing screamed at her.  That was a blessing.  <br>
<br>
She timidly cast a light heal spell on her bumped head, which relieved the pounding, at any rate.  And brightened the cavern enough to show her that, while the front entrance was gone, the rest of the tunnel was pretty intact.  Lots of boulders everywhere, and the snow drift....but the dust had settled.<br>
<br>
She summoned a lightstone, cast eyes of the cat on herself, and searched her immediate area.  Her staff was on the floor, close to where she'd woken up.  She bent down to pick it up and heard a scrambling noise.  More boulders?  An aftershock?  She braced herself, standing still, looking around.  <br>
<br>
Nothing.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hello?&quot; she called out, almost whispering for fear of disturbing the silence.<br>
<br>
Nothing.<br>
<br>
Then, a giggle.  Very small, very quiet...and she wasn't at all sure which direction it was coming from.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hello!  Hello there!  Who's here?&quot;  she cried.  <br>
<br>
Silence answered her.<br>
<br>
&quot;Have it your way....&quot;  Irritated, she picked up her bag which had tumbled intact to the floor, hefted it to her shoulders, and said &quot;I'm off to find a way out of here!  If you care to show yourself, please do so at your leisure.&quot;  And, taking the other route from the one she had taken that morning, she gingerly set off down the trail, taking care to mark her passage with coal.<br>
<br>
Behind her, silently, something followed.  Erasing the coal marks of Tunare that Melba was leaving on the walls at her every turn. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umelbatoast.showPublicProfile?language=EN>melbatoast</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 104<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/3/01 4:59:05 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Wood Elves</span><hr size=1> Melba continued following the twisting tunnel down inside the mountain range.  It was never very steep, but it switched back and forth quite a bit, and sometimes even seemed to go up.  At one point, Melba’s head started aching again.  She sat against the cavern wall and had some dried fruit and a bit of water, and rested.  Her mana rejuvenated (she’d been casting buffs like crazy, to keep her strength and stamina up), she did a full healing on her poor head.  Thus refreshed, she trudged on.<br>
<br>
From time to time, she heard the scrambling behind her.  But when she’d try to track it, nothing was there.  No footprints, no smell, no sound.    Nevertheless, she kept her Ykesha slightly un-hooked from her belt, ready.<br>
<br>
The tunnel had been going up for some time when she heard a noise ahead of her.  No giggling, no scrambling, but a real noise.  Rocks being moved.  Heavy rocks.<br>
<br>
“Hullo there!” she called, skirting around a pile of silt that had collected from a recent overhead cave-in.<br>
<br>
“Shhhhh!!” she was shushed.  “Please!  You’ll start another one with all that carrying on!!”<br>
<br>
“  “ she replied (rangers do know when to shush).  But she didn’t think she’d been carrying on, just saying “Hullo there”.  She headed towards the voice, and soon came upon a wood elf, or rather, half of a wood elf, sticking out of the side of the cavern wall.<br>
<br>
“Oh, blessed mother of us all!” she cried, in a whisper, and dropped her pack on the ground.  She ran to him and began to whisk the pebbles away from his face, as they fell in trickles from the top of the hole from which he was emerging.  “Here, let me help….”<br>
<br>
“Yes, do.  Please grab my arms and pull.  You haven’t any troll oil, have you??” he looked at her beseechingly.<br>
<br>
“Troll oil?  No.  Sorry.  No.  Nor a barbarian who could shrink you!” she smiled.   He grimaced.  “Sorry….” She said, and took a firm grip on his forearms.  With her foot leveraged against the downslope of the cavern wall, she yanked.  And yanked some more.  By little bits, he moved.  Then, just as she was despairing that he’d lodged himself against some boulder, he popped through.  They both went flying across the cavern, while a cold wind blew through the little hole.  She picked herself up off the floor. <br>
<br>
“Are you ok??” she asked him.<br>
<br>
“Fine, now,” he grinned from the pile of silt he was lying on.  “Thanks!  Ranger, yes?   Me too.  I think we saw each other, a week or so ago…at the entrance.  The spelunkers?”  He extended a hand.<br>
<br>
“Oh yes, yes, that was you?”  she nodded, shaking his outstretched hand.  “How goes the spelunking?  Or, better yet, here’s another question.  Did you hear the explosion?  And do you know we’re trapped in here?  And do you know a way out?”<br>
<br>
“I don’t know myself, as I’m more the excavation/hole man, but they might….” He said, pointing at the hole he’d just been forcibly ejected from.  She walked over and peered down, and was surprised to see two sets of eyes blinking at her.  “Hullo, there, spelunkers!” she called quietly through the hole.  “Coming through?<br>
<br>
There was discussion and more discussion, and eventually a sort of shovel was passed through the hole.  The spelunker she had pulled through took it and began, very carefully, to widen the hole.  “OK, fellahs, I think you’re good.  Give it a try….”<br>
<br>
One by one, the band of wood elf rangers squeezed through the hole, and stood brushing themselves off, eyeing Melba.<br>
<br>
“What’s this about an explosion?” one of them asked.<br>
<br>
Melba explained about her adventure, about seeing Tunare (at which they were appropriately impressed, aghast, and at the same time, suspicious), about her run to the entrance, and then the avalanche.  <br>
<br>
“An avalanche?  Not an explosion?” the one who had spoken before asked.<br>
<br>
“Well, it sounded like an explosion, but it could’ve been rocks falling, now that I think of it.  Or snow.  I don’t know.  Do avalanches sound like an explosion??” she asked.  The wood elves shrugged.  They were only here on an explorer’s holiday, and to tell the truth, weren’t too happy with all the snow.<br>
<br>
Then she told them about the scrabbling and the giggling.  They peered behind them, down the tunnel where Melba had emerged.  They had no ideas.  “Could be anything, really” one of them muttered.<br>
<br>
“Tea?” one of them asked, suddenly.  Melba was astonished by their casual attitude about being trapped forever in a cold, dark cavern.   But still, she shared their tea, and even passed around some dried pears (“Delightful!” one of them cried).<br>
<br>
Just then, another boom and a thud shook the cavern.  “Oh, THAT!” one of the rangers said.  “That’s been going on for days!  You’ve only just felt it?”<br>
<br>
Melba looked at him.<br>
<br>
“Spring thaw, my dear.  Spring thaw,” he wiped a drop of tea from his lower lip.  He looked at her in a side glance, “Err,  Melba, dear, what’s your dragon faction??  Do you know?”<br>
<br>
She set her teacup down on the saucer (these wood elves….).  “Well,” she said, swallowing, “I think it’s ok!  I mean, I’ve never fought one, and I’ve always rather admired them.  So, really, I think it should be ok!  Why?”  She looked around nervously.<br>
<br>
“Ah, no reason.  If it’s good, then that’s all that matters.  Look, we’re staying in, or rather, going on with our travels,  because we know the other entrance to this place…and it’s YONKS from here.  And tiny holes…you’d have to….but no!  You’d never make it with us, though, being human .  I mean, my dear, you’re no Barbarian, but look at you!  So tall! That bosom! tsk.  No, no, we’ll have to show you the other way out…..”<br>
<br>
At that, the woodelves drained their teacups, packed them away, and with much joviality and jostling, they stood before her, ready to push on.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/umelbatoast.showPublicProfile?language=EN>melbatoast</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/4/01 1:39:09 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Wood Elves?</span><hr size=1> Melba couldn’t decide if the wood elves were to be trusted.  Sure, they were friendly, and shared their tea, but something in their manner…they didn’t seem all that worried about the explosions resounding through the caverns.  She decided she really had very little choice but to follow them, however.  If they knew a way out, they knew a way out!<br>
<br>
Off they all marched, down the corridor…or rather up, as the path in this section was still veering upwards.<br>
<br>
“What was in that other cavern?” Melba asked the one she had pulled through.<br>
<br>
“Oh, just the old mines...” he answered.<br>
<br>
Melba lifted her arms.  “Figures.  I’ve been looking for those all day!”<br>
<br>
“There’s not much in them.  And besides, you can’t get to them from your entrance…well, you can NOW, what with the hole.  We had to walk all the way to the other entrance, and then back down through a separate, hidden tunnel, to get to the mines.” He explained.<br>
<br>
They trudged on in silence for a bit.<br>
<br>
“What are you and that warrior doing down here, anyway?  I mean, there’s nothing to hunt.  And you’re NOT spelunkers….” He glanced at her.<br>
<br>
“No, not spelunking,” she grinned.  “Mostly just exploring.  Killing palls after awhile, you know?  We thought we’d see more of Velious, before it became the tourist trap that Kunark has become.”<br>
<br>
The wood elf nodded in agreement.  “Aye.  One of the reasons we’re here is to get away from the overcrowding in Greater Faydark.  You wouldn’t believe how bad it’s gotten there.  And so many beggars!  You can’t just enjoy your day, like you used to.  Always someone asking for a handout….” He shook his head.<br>
<br>
The strode on in companionable silence for a ways.   At a crossroads in the passageway, the wood elf in the lead called a halt, and they all stopped.  “This” he said imperiously “is it.”  He pointed down the path, into the dark tunnel.<br>
<br>
“It’s going down” she said.<br>
<br>
He nodded, putting his thumbs through his leiderhosen straps.  Had he been wearing those before? she wondered.    “Aye, you must go down into the deepest part of the caverns, before it leads you to a steep path that takes you up.  It’ll put you out about ½ mile from where you entered, I reckon.”<br>
<br>
“He reckons?” she thought.  “Sounds like a halfling….”<br>
<br>
“Er…ok, then,” she said aloud.  “Thanks much for your assistance!  And good luck!  But please, do rethink leaving.  I really do think that something bad is about to happen in this cavern, and it’d be safer for everyone if we all got out!”<br>
<br>
One of them nodded, one of them shuffled his feet, the other cleared his throat to say something, but thought better of it.  The last one…the leader, smiled a bit, then let out a strange little giggle.<br>
<br>
“We’ll be fine, milady.  You just take care.  You’ll be out of here before you know it.”<br>
<br>
They all bowed to her simultaneously, and headed up the path that was still winding upwards.<br>
<br>
Melba looked down the dark path, considered it for a moment, and then moved into the darkness.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
Back at the cave entrance, Damdor was still digging.  The Wurmslayer had turned out be a red herring.  It must’ve been flung from the cavern by some sort of force, for as much as he dug, he couldn’t find any indication that there had ever been a cavern entrance here.<br>
<br>
He had no idea how long ago the cave in happened, but by the looks of the snowpack, it was shortly after he’d left her.   He had to keep digging.  There was nothing else he could do.  He couldn’t just leave her there.  Not if there was a chance….<br>
