<br>
Hours later, the path leveled out a bit.  She noticed that the dark was decreasing, she could see further into the tunnel.  Soon, a strange glow loomed ahead of her.  The glow got brighter, and eventually she came to a large, domed cavern, bisected by a stream.  The stream had that strange glow, like the one leading to Thurgadin..  Lying next to the stream was a mummified Shardwurm.  <br>
<br>
“Now, how on Norrath did that thing get in here?” she wondered.<br>
<br>
She surveyed the cavern, finding a likely spot to get some rest.  It had been a long day…and she wasn’t sure what time it was.  She just knew that she was exhausted.  She dropped her backpack on the ground and lay down,  head resting on her pack, regretting not having her bedroll.   The jolts had decreased, over the hours of her solitary walk, and there hadn’t been on in the last couple of hours.<br>
<br>
She pondered the high domed ceiling of the cavern, admiring the play of light from the stream on the stalactites.   She said a quiet prayer to Tunare, asking her to keep her safe while she slept, and to not let Damdor worry too much about her.<br>
 <br>
She was just drifting off when she heard a voice.  A quiet, whisper of a voice.  It was coming from this side of  the stream, to her left, but behind a large boulder.  Quietly, she rose to her feet and, hugging the cavern wall, tiptoed  along the wall.  Peeking around the boulder, she saw a girl.<br>
<br>
The girl was on her side, curled up in an almost fetal position, rocking slightly.  But then Melba noticed that one of her legs was sticking out at a strange angle.  The girl was humming.  Or was she praying?  Melba couldn’t tell.   She stayed still against the boulder, thinking of a way to announce her presence without startling the girl.  It was too late.  She saw the girl tense up, and try to turn herself over.<br>
<br>
“No, no, no, please.  Don’t hurt me!” she whispered, her voice full of tears and pain.  Melba dashed from behind the rock and kneeled in front of the girl.  She saw she was a high elf, very pretty, very young.  But shabbily dressed, which was unusual, for a high elf.<br>
<br>
“Oh, no, of course I won’t!  Let me help you!”  Melba was about to cast healing on the girl, when she suddenly grabbed her hands.<br>
<br>
“No!  No spells!”  She seemed terrified.<br>
<br>
“What?  Why ever not?  You need to be healed!” Melba whispered back.  Alarmed by the girl’s refusal of healing, she glanced around, expecting something to be coming at them.<br>
<br>
The girl took in a rasping sob of a breath, and said “It’ll attract them.  We don’t want to attract them!!”  The girl was obviously delirious with pain.<br>
<br>
Melba looked at the girl, and considered the situation.<br>
<br>
“Ok, no spells.  But at least let me make you more comfortable.  I need to put your leg bone back in line. It’ll heal on it’s own, naturally, with time, but only if we can straighten it.”  The girl looked at her with lovely green, almond shaped eyes.  Her eyes were calm, which was in direct opposition to the tone of her voice.<br>
<br>
“Will it hurt?” she asked tremulously.<br>
<br>
“Yes” Melba couldn’t lie to her.  “But I’ve got a flask full of brandy.  That may help dull the pain a bit.”<br>
<br>
The girl nodded. And tried to right herself.  Melba stood and, putting her arms under the girl’s arms from behind her, dragged her away from the stream and towards a small indented area in the wall.  She propped the girl up there, and ran back for her pack behind the boulder.  She rummaged through the bag, and handed her the flask.  “Take a good swallow, ok?”  The girl nodded and did so, shuddering.<br>
<br>
“Good, ok.  Here, grab onto my staff and squeeze it with both hands, tightly.  It’ll help with the pain.&quot;  She hoped.  “My mother gave me that staff, before I left home for my first ever ranger job” she said, talking to divert the girl’s attention away from what she was about to do.  “It’s very precious to me.  I’m sure the love she put into it will help you with the pain.  Squeeze hard!” she said.<br>
<br>
She grabbed the girl’s boot, and when the girl opened her mouth to say something, she yanked the leg toward herself, and twisted it to the right.  There was a crack, then another, then a pop.  The girl screamed, and kept screaming.  Melba made sure the leg was aligned, and shuffled around to the girl’s head.  She grabbed the flask and poured a bit into the girl’s mouth.   Before closing the flask, Melba took a sip.  The brandy burned her throat, but she felt her insides go warm.<br>
<br>
The girl was whimpering now, wringing the staff with her hands.  Melba stroked her hair and let her cry.<br>
<br>
“Better?”  Melba asked after a long while.<br>
<br>
“A little,” the girl whispered through clenched teeth.<br>
<br>
“You were very brave,&quot; she said, smiling.  &quot;My name’s Melba Lyteheart.  I’m a Ranger, guided by the blessing and love of Tunare.  What’s your name?”<br>
<br>
“F…Firiona,” the girl replied.  Melba raised her eyebrows.  The girl smiled weakly.  “No.  Not that Firiona.  Mother just named me after her.  She admired her….spirit….”<br>
<br>
Melba smiled and nodded.  The girl panted a bit, fighting a wave of nausea and pain, and then coughed.  But she’d stopped crying.<br>
<br>
“Now, can you tell me what you’re doing here??” Melba asked.<br>
<br>
“I was….trying to find…the mines.”<br>
<br>
“Is there a treasure or something?”<br>
<br>
She shook her head slightly.  “No.  Pilgrimage.  Holy relics are thought to be…..lost in them.  But I’ve failed.  I’ve been down here for weeks!”<br>
<br>
Weeks!  Melba couldn’t imagine it.  Where was her stuff?  Why was her leg broken?<br>
<br>
As if hearing her unasked question, the girl pointed up towards the ceiling.  “That last large shaking….I was exploring a small tunnel, and the floor collapsed, and I ended up here.”<br>
<br>
That was quite a long fall.  Melba was astonished the girl wasn’t dead.  <br>
<br>
They sat in silence for awhile, and the girl finally drifted off to sleep.  Melba gently removed the girl’s head from her lap, and scooted sideways.   She took a small leather tunic out of her pack, folded it up, and put it under Firiona’s head.  She stood with her hands on her hips, looking around the cavern for something to make a splint with.  No wood, as usual, she frowned.  Wurm bones?  She grimaced at the thought of carving up that beast.  Besides, Wurm bones were porous and would probably break easily.  She needed something really straight, really hard, and …. She looked at her staff, lying on the ground next to Firiona’s open hand.  She knew it was the only solution.<br>
<br>
She grabbed her Ykesha from the pile of her belongings she’s discarded when she popped the High Elf’s leg back in place.  “Shame to use the blade to hack a piece of wood” she thought “but oh well.”  She placed the blade’s tip in a central spot at the top of the staff and tapped it gently with her boot.  And again, until it was wedged firmly into the staff.  Then she began to move the blade back and forth until she heard a cracking.  The staff split neatly in half.  She used the blade to saw the staff in half again.  Her Ykesha was now useless for a fight, but perhaps it would still process.  That was something, at least.  She tied the two flat surfaces of the bottom half of the staff to Firona’s leg with strips of leather from her undertunic.  Firiona stirred once, whimpering quietly, and slept again.  The splint in place, Melba collapsed onto the ground next to the girl, and slept for hours.<br>
