<br>
<br>
When she woke, she found Firiona sitting up, admiring her splinted leg.  The girl smiled at her and said “Good morning!  Or, good evening.  Who knows for sure….”<br>
<br>
“Glad to see you sitting up!  Are you feeling better?”  Melba asked, sitting up, herself.  She reached for her backpack and began to rummage through it.<br>
<br>
“Yes, a lot.  Thanks.  It still hurts, but not so much.  I had some more brandy…” she said sheepishly, handing Melba the flask.  Melba shook it…half empty.  She grinned at the girl.  “Not too drunk to try to find our way out of here, are you?”<br>
<br>
Firiona smiled and said “It takes a lot more than a shot of brandy to get me drunk, my lady.”  Melba didn’t pause to consider how a High Elf so young could have such a high Alcohol Tolerance.  She’d found her bag of fishrolls, and passed one to Firiona.  <br>
<br>
“I’m afraid they may be a bit stale, but the fish is smoked, and should be ok.”  She stood.  “I wonder if we can drink this stream water?”<br>
<br>
Firiona shook her head.  “I wouldn’t.” <br>
<br>
“You’re most likely right….” Melba answered.  “Ah well, we should be out of here, soon enough.  There’s plenty of water, outside!  And the faster we get out of here the better, now that we’re weaponless.…”  <br>
<br>
“We have no weapons?”  the girl looked up at her questioningly.<br>
<br>
“Nope.  I used the staff to splint your leg, and my sword to chop the staff.  I can have it sharpened, of course, but….”<br>
<br>
“You chopped up your staff, for me?  You ruined your lovely sword, for me?” She stared in amazement at Melba.  <br>
<br>
“Well, of course!  Anyone would have.”<br>
<br>
Firiona shook her head.  “Actually, that’s not true….” She said.  “Followers of Bristlebane, for instance, wouldn’t do it.  In fact, they wouldn’t think twice about misleading a wandering ranger….”  Firiona was muttering now, staring at her splint, looking around the cavern.<br>
<br>
“Melba, what are you doing in these caverns??” Firiona asked, suddenly.<br>
<br>
Melba told her the tale of how she and her husband Damdor had come here to explore, how she had gotten trapped in the cave, and how she had reached this cavern, in time to help the injured Firiona.  She told her about seeing Tunare (Firiona frowned slightly, at that), and the group of wood elf rangers (at which Firiona nodded, almost sullenly).  She told her about the giggling and the scrambling and the jolts.  Firiona frowned, and continued to frown, and continued to look around the cavern, listening for something, it seemed….<br>
<br>
“What’s wrong?” Melba asked, disturbed.   “Do you hear something?  And what’s all that you were saying about Bristlebane?”<br>
<br>
Firiona turned her gaze on Melba once more.  She took a deep breath.  “Lady Ranger, I’m afraid I’ve been dishonest with you.  I can’t say I’m ashamed…it was necessary, though, as you could very well have been sent here to disrupt my task.”<br>
<br>
Melba boggled.  “Disrupt your task?  Finding the relics?”<br>
<br>
Firiona shifted her weight and tried to bend her leg a little.  She rearranged the splint a little bit, and was able to bend her knee a fraction of an inch.  She looked up at Melba, who was standing above her, hands on hips.<br>
<br>
“I’m not here on a pilgrimage.  I’m here to save lives.”<br>
<br>
Melba raised her eyebrows and continued to listen.<br>
<br>
Firiona looked at the ground and took a breath.  “I was sent here by….well, you don’t need to know that.  I was asked to come here to search for a dragon.”<br>
<br>
Melba was quiet a moment. Frowning, she asked “To kill it?”<br>
<br>
“Oh no no!!  Not that.  Not ever that.  The dragon is one of the lives I’m to save.”<br>
<br>
“From whom??”<br>
<br>
Firiona sighed.  “To cut a really long and potentially tedious story short, from Bristlebane.  He kidnapped a dragon who we believe to be Veeshan…” Melba gasped.  “Yes, it’s too horrid to think about, but it’s true…” Firiona continued.   “He’s holding her captive.  We think, here.”<br>
<br>
“Who’s this ‘we’, Firiona?” Melba asked.<br>
<br>
The High Elf looked up at Melba and said “Regretfully, I can’t tell you that, right now.” <br>
<br>
“I’ll accept that, for now.”<br>
<br>
Firiona smiled.  “I was sure you would!  Now, can you help me?  There’s isn’t much time left.  The dragon…she’s the one causing all these earthquakes and explosions and avalanches.  Fizzlethorpe, the wily old bastard, trapped her in a cavern like this one, only a bit larger.  He thinks that one of her many children, long ago, hid some fabulous treasure here in these caverns.  Which is absolute nonsense, but Bristlebane doesn’t know that.  He’s such a fool!” she spat.  This girl does not seem to be the same meek, injured elf I found yesterday, Melba thought to herself.  “He’s trapped her and won’t let her out until she tells him where the treasure is.”  She pounded the ground with her fists, sending up little clouds of dust.  She stared up at the ceiling for a moment, wiped her hands together to get the dust off, and took a deep breath.  <br>
<br>
Firiona, recomposed, looked up at Melba, and smiled.  “Veeshan is trapped in a cavern, and is destroying it.  She’ll destroy this entire mountain range, to get out of here.  There’s a City on the other side of this range, you know.  She’ll destroy the city, once she’s destroyed the range.  She’ll kill countless numbers of people, if we don’t free her.”<br>
<br>
“The elves…the dwarves….” Melba began.<br>
<br>
“Yes, the group of dwarves and elves you saw….they’re all dead.  Trapped under rocks.  We can’t help them.  But we can help ourselves, and Veeshan.”<br>
<br>
“But, how do you know the elves are dead?  I just saw them yesterday! They lead me here!”<br>
<br>
Firiona shook her head.  “They weren’t rangers.  They were Bristlebane.”<br>
<br>
Melba opened her mouth for a moment, and shut it again.  Then said “What, all of them?”<br>
<br>
Firiona nodded.  Melba looked at the ceiling.  “That little bastard trickster…” she muttered.<br>
<br>
Firiona nodded again.  “You see how he works.  He led you down here…saying it was an exit…when really, it was just taking you deeper into danger, and closer to the dragon.  Who WILL kill you, if she doesn’t know any better.”<br>
<br>
Melba picked at the piece of dried pear in her hands.  How was she supposed to absorb all of this?  What was she supposed to say to this poor injured High Elf girl who seemed to know so much about the gods, and about dragons.<br>
<br>
“You….how do you know all this?  Why you??”<br>
<br>
“I can’t tell you that right now.  I wish I could.  I will later.  But now, we’ve GOT to get going….”<br>
<br>
“But…your leg?”<br>
<br>
“Oh.” said Firiona, looking down at her splinted limb.  “That’ll heal.  Just DON’T cast any spells on me, ok?  Promise, Melba?  Now, help me up….”  The girl started to pull herself up, using the wall to steady her leg.  Melba stood and grabbed her arm to steady her other side.  Firiona stood, tested her leg, and grimaced.  <br>
<br>
“It’ll hurt for a long, long while.  Why don’t we just find our way out of here, and send someone back?”<br>
<br>
Firiona shook her head.  “I’ll be fine.  I just need a little time.  But I can’t leave Veeshan here.  It’s imperative that we get to her.”  Melba looked at the girl, saw the determination and compassion in her eyes, and nodded. <br>
<br>
“How can I not help?” Melba asked her, smiling.  Firiona smiled back.<br>
<br>
“Good!  Let’s get going, then….”<br>
<br>
To Melba’s surprise, the girl began to hop on her good leg.   Then, tentatively, she put a little of her weight on her broken one…then more, and did a little hop/walk.  Then she was walking, suddenly, with a limp, but still walking.  “See?” she smiled at Melba.  “Not so bad at all!  High Elves heal fast…” she added, as an afterthought.<br>
<br>
“I guess so….” Melba said, uncertainly.  She picked her pack and sword and remaining staff pieces up off the ground, and followed slowly along after Firiona, anticipating that the girl would eventually fall and break her other leg.  She never did fall.<br>
