Firiona’s leg seemed to heal itself, the more she walked on it.  The High Elf lead them across the stream, past the long-dead Wurm (“Poor thing…a child of Veeshan, no doubt…” Firiona whispered), and through another entrance to the cavern.  They continued down the tunnel.<br>
<br>
“Why have the explosions stopped?” Melba asked.<br>
<br>
“Either she’s asleep, she’s escaped (one can only hope), or she’s dead.” Firiona answered, ominously.<br>
<br>
As if in answer to Melba’s query, they heard a loud crash and the ground jumped under their feet.  Melba grabbed at Firiona’s arm to hold her up, but the High Elf had steadied herself and was listening.<br>
<br>
“That way,” she pointed to a branch in the tunnel that was heading, miraculously, up.  They quickened their pace as much as they could, and headed up.<br>
<br>
The ground began to shake violently, in five minute intervals.  “We’re getting closer,” Firiona whispered.  “No spells, now…you’ll only frighten her.  Or anger her.”  Melba nodded.<br>
<br>
Fifteen minutes later, they came to a door.  A large, wooden, bolted door.  They looked at each other.  “What now?” Melba asked.<br>
<br>
“I don’t suppose you can pick locks…” Firiona said.<br>
<br>
“Errrm, no, ‘fraid not….”  Melba looked around the door.  The hinges were rusted to the doorframe.  The lock looked very old, and a bit rusty.  “How about this?”  Melba unhooked her damaged Ykesha from her belt.  “It’s already needing repair.  A little more won’t hurt….”<br>
<br>
She timed it so that her Ykesha striking the lock coincided with the explosions.   They had to wait agonizing minutes for the next one, but on the third try, the poor trusty damaged sword managed to break the lock.  “The old fashioned way,” Melba said.<br>
<br>
“Thank the gods it didn’t process!” Firiona muttered.<br>
<br>
“Hardly ever does…” Melba grinned at her.<br>
<br>
“Ok, quiet now…..” Firiona put her hand in the doorhandle and gently pulled.  There was only a rust scraping noise, but it was soft.  She peaked in…and pulled the door open a bit more.  All was darkness.   They could see nothing, but Melba couldn’t cast her sight spell. They could tell, by the resonance of sound, that the chamber was a big one.  Firiona rummaged in her dusty leather tunic pants and pulled out a small candle and a flint.  “Always come prepared, when magic may fail you…” she said.  She lit the candle, holding it gingerly between two fingers.  She peered into the darkness.<br>
<br>
Something was coming at them…something large, and red, was coming towards the door, at a speed greater almost than their eyes could follow it.<br>
<br>
“Back!” Firiona shouted.  Too late.   She and Melba were thrown by the force of wind and dust across the cavern and into the wall.  The flickering candle was lying on the ground, but Melba could still see what was at the door.  A large, red dragon tail, twitching.  Scales battered and dusty.  <br>
<br>
Firiona jumped to her feet as quickly as she could, hopping on her good leg.  She scooped up the candle and headed towards the door.  “We’ve got to stop her.  She’s hurting herself.”<br>
<br>
The High Elf went straight for the tail, and pushed on it.  At first, it didn’t move.  She pushed again, and again.  The tail twitched and slithered past the door.  In moments, it was replaced by the flaring nostrils of a dragon’s snout.  The dragon took a deep breath.<br>
<br>
“Veeshan, no!”  Firiona cried.<br>
<br>
“And why shouldn’t I, jailer!” the dragon rumbled at her.<br>
<br>
“I am not your jailer, Veeshan.  Bristlebane is the one who keeps you trapped here.  We are here to free you!”<br>
<br>
A great golden eye appeared at the door, tilting up and down to get a look.<br>
<br>
The dragon exhaled.  “Tunare??!!” <br>
<br>
Firiona smiled at the dragon.  “Yes, my dear old lady.  It’s Tunare.”<br>
<br>
Melba gasped and took a step backwards.  “But…You look nothing like the Tunare I saw in the cavern, the other day.”<br>
<br>
Firiona/Tunare motioned Melba to be still and quiet.  “Veeshan, dear, will you move back a bit so we can get in there with you?”  The dragon obliged.    Firiona/Tunare stepped through the door, Melba cautiously moving in behind her.<br>
<br>
“Veeshan, all this pounding you’re doing is destroying this mountain range!  Killing innocent people!”<br>
<br>
“There are no innocent people,” the dragon growled at the goddess.  “All are evil.  All should perish!”<br>
<br>
“Now, Veeshan, you know you don’t feel that way.  Look, I have a human here with me.  Is she a threat to you??”<br>
<br>
Veeshan peered down at Melba.  She lowered her massive head and put her mouth right in front of Melba’s head.  Melba was quaking inside, but stood her ground.  Veeshan’s massive tongue rolled out of her mouth, and she gave Melba a bit of a lick on the top of her head.    Veeshan reared back on her haunches.<br>
<br>
“No.  She has good faction with the Children of the Wurmqueen.  I will not eat her.”  Melba exhaled, unaware that she had been holding her breath.<br>
<br>
Tunare smiled at Melba.  For Melba realized that indeed she HAD to be the goddess, if she spoke thus with dragons, and came to no harm.<br>
<br>
“What now?” Melba asked, looking feebly around the cavern.  She couldn’t see the walls.  The light from their candle wasn’t even able to illuminate the entire dragon.<br>
<br>
“What now??” Veeshan roared with laughter.  The cavern walls shook.  “What now, she asks!!  Tunare, now!”<br>
<br>
Tunare glanced at Melba.  “All I needed to do was get to her.  Touch her.  I can pop us out of here, no trouble.”<br>
<br>
“All this time…you could’ve just ‘popped’ us out of here?”<br>
<br>
“I thought you would like to come with me.  And I knew you were trustworthy,” Tunare answered.<br>
<br>
“How?!”  Melba asked  “How did you know?  I could’ve been one of Bristlebane’s tricksters, like the others!”  Melba looked from the dragon to the goddess.  &quot;And another thing...why no spells?  Why couldn't I heal you?&quot;<br>
<br>
“If you had cast a spell on me, healing or not, Melba, every creature, dead or alive, who falls under my protection would've been after your blood. It's just the way it is, I'm afraid.&quot;  Tunare smiled at her.<br>
<br>
&quot;As for the other thing, you did a selfless act.  You destroyed your weapons, to help me.  You didn’t consider for a moment that you might need them to fight your way out of here.  You just did it.  That proved to me that you were trustworthy.  And a kindly-regarded child of … well, me!”  Tunare grinned again.  Melba stood in silent contemplation, realizing the praise that Tunare gave her was worth more than her life; more than anything she’d ever known.  <br>
<br>
Her contemplation was interrupted when Veeshan roared “Hop on, ladies!”<br>
<br>
Tunare climbed up to the dragon’s neck, and reached down for Melba.  Melba took her hand, and climbed up behind her.  <br>
<br>
“Perfectly safe,” Tunare muttered to her. “Hold on.” <br>
<br>
Tunare glowed golden from every vein, and then all was blackness.<br>
<br>
The popped out, high above the city of Thurgadin.  The cold wind whipped Melba’s hair into her face, and she held tighter onto Tunare’s waist.<br>
<br>
Tunare turned and regarded her.  “I’m getting off here.  I’ve got some dwarven miners to talk to.  We’ve got to get those caves completely sealed up so no more rangers die.  You know how they do like to wander into places they shouldn’t!”<br>
<br>
Melba grinned at her.  “What about Bristlebane?” she asked.<br>
<br>
“I’ll take care of him, later.  And you can be SURE Veeshan won’t be caught again, so easily.”  Tunare patted the old dragon on the shoulder.  Veeshan snorted.   Tunare grasped Melba’s hand.  “Thank you so much for your help.  You’ve earned my respect.  Maybe one day I can repay you for your kindness.  Some new spells, or something.  We’ll see…..”  she grinned, touched Melba’s cheek lightly, and disappeared.<br>
<br>
“Hmph,” snorted Veeshan.  “Where to, human?”<br>
<br>
Melba shifted a bit on Veeshan’s neck and said “Can you find my husband?”<br>
<br>
“Find him!  I can smell him!  He’s been digging for HOURS!  Get him a hot bath, would you?”<br>
<br>
Melba laughed as Veeshan banked gently over a snow covered hill and headed towards the hidden cavern entrance where Melba’s dear husband was still digging through the snow.<br>
<br>
*******<br>
<br>
Damdor heard the whooshing before he could see anything.  Standing, leaning against his Wurmslayer, he peered into the distance.  The sun glared off the melting snow.   He’d been digging for 6 hours….finding nothing.  He despaired of any interruption of his search.  But this was definitely an interruption he couldn’t ignore.  Heading towards him across the snowfield, flying at a low altitude, was a giant red dragon.<br>
<br>
“What the….?” He hefted the Wurmslayer to fighting position, determined to stand his ground against the beast, which was obviously headed straight for him.  At least he would fight dying, and die near Melba’s resting place.  <br>
<br>
The roar of the wind caused by the dragon’s wings beating against the snow became deafening as it grew closer.  Snow flurries eddied around underneath her wings, glistening in the sunlight. The dragon came to a position about 100 yards away from the warrior, and backpedaled her wings.  Flapping gently, she landed in the snow with a grunt.  She grinned at him, tongue hanging out of her mouth.<br>
<br>
All Damdor could do was stare.  Then, he thought he should bow.  So he bowed to the dragon.  She roared with amusement.<br>
<br>
“Another human with honor!  I am all astonishment.  Sir, I would bow myself, but as you see, I am old and tired and battered and in no position to be bowing to anyone.   But I bring you something that I believe belongs with you.”  Veeshan turned her head and looked behind her.<br>
<br>
Melba slid from the dragon’s neck to the snow with a thump.  She turned and looked the dragon in the eyes.   The golden eyes glowed at her.  Melba bent on one knee and saluted Veeshan.<br>
<br>
“Oh, Ranger, no need for that!  Your  smelly human over there already did that.  Up.  Up!  Off with you!  And my gratitude, you know.  Accept it.  It’s yours.”  The dragon hooted softly and tapped Melba’s shoulder with her wingtip.  “Off with you!” <br>
<br>
Melba stepped back a ways, and the dragon gathered herself and sprang heavily into the air.  She flew off over the snowy hills, in the direction of Iceclad Ocean.  Melba watched her go.  <br>
<br>
She turned and saw Damdor, standing very still against the snowy hill, Wurmslayer still in his hand in a half salute.  The weapon fell out of his hand, into the snow.  She trudged to him through the shimmering, slush, grinning ear to ear.<br>
<br>
“Hi, hon!  Where are those cream-filled dwarf cakes you promised me??”<br>
<br>
Damdor embraced his wife with such force that she thought he would crack her ribs.  She didn’t mind at all.<br>
